posts.com:
/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

>>71639502
Your type is probably quite similar to mine, and you brought up some interesting points in your post.

>the same character, who I suppose is like an idealised, sanitised...reflection of myself
Sometimes it does make you stop, think, and introspect - how much of this character, or ideal, reflects you? And how much of yourself do you see reflected in this character? I tend to believe that "like attracts like" instead of "opposites attract", regarding romantic matters. At least, it's the school of thought I follow. There is some overlap between desired traits, and one's own traits, and that overlap is quite large. larger than I'd admit It's certainly different for others - some seek those who are different from themselves for a different perspective, or because they'd find being with one similar to themselves to be too monotonous. But it's not for me.
>appearance is not very consistent
People's taste/preference also change over time. Looking at my own folder, I do notice subtle differences in what I've made, but in general, my preferences have remained more or less the same. Some inconsistencies were also simply due to the limitations of the specific picrew maker I used. I sometimes don't like how a maker portrays something, and I have to settle for the next best alternative it has. Rarely I'll even end up almost finishing with a maker and then decide something looks wrong and scrap it all. If possible, I'll sometimes also make two versions of her wearing casual/non-casual attire.

Maybe I'll also make a collage.

>>71640928
I don't think I engage with this on the "waifuism" level that is the basis for most of these threads. Even if I wanted to I don't think I could bring myself to do it. If others post characters defined as their "type" or some fictionalised character to construct elaborate fantasies, that's great, but it's not what I'm after.

Rather, the posts are more a reflection on "how I'd be". The physical appearance, at least, (not that picrews are any good at representing that) are more or less directly based on myself. When, in the past, the threads tended to feature posters describing the character they made, I tended to write out a few attributes inherited from myself. These aspects, of course, were cherry-picked for what might have been interesting or funny; nevertheless, they are derived from how I perceive myself and how others perceive me. Never mind if the clothing in which the character's depicted is an unlikely taste: it more so reflects how I myself dress (or would dress, if I had more money).

There are some variations, of course. In reality I have uncorrected vision, but myopia runs in the family, so the picrews always reflect that. This fictionalised self-inversion, being fictional, of course makes fewer mistakes, is more amicable, less abrasive, etc. than the real deal. Yet it's (I won't deign to use personal pronouns for such a fragment of the imagination) is not fundamentally much altered from the maker. That's also why I played around with pictures of the same character in differently-gendered incarnations. Fundamentally I want to test and see how I (and others, I guess) respond to gender variations of the same internal concept. It's very grounding, I think, and I try to gain a healthy understanding of both moids and foids, something which most on this board seem to lack.

And yes, I agree on all points with the flaws of Picrew itself.

Evolutionary theory implies that altruistic social systems are self-defeating. This implication is so obvious that a special label was invented to dismiss it without argument: "Social Darwinism". If a society subsidizes free rider reproduction, as the modern welfare state does, that society will eventually collapse due to the accumulation of a large free rider population. The modern welfare is unstable because it is self-defeating. It requires an ever-increasing input of energy to sustain itself as the population degrades.
Evolutionary theory implies that charity isn't really altruistic in the long run. Charity might allow a large population of useless people to survive and reproduce, but that population will eventually perish when our civilization either collapses or changes to be less altruistic. Charity in general is futile unless it has a compensating mechanism to limit free rider reproduction. We understand this principle well enough when it applies to geese or ground squirrels ("Don't Feed the Wildlife"), but we ignore it when it applies to human beings. Even if you accept the premise that we have altruistic moral obligations, charity fails because altruism is self-defeating.
Some will try to argue that altruism is not self-defeating. That argument almost always invokes some magical mechanism that transcends evolution. The gist is that we don't need to worry about free rider reproduction because our human specialness exempts us from evolution, somehow. The problem will be solved by some non-evolutionary process, such as demographic transition, or we will deal with it using some hypothetical technology, so it won't really be a problem. These arguments rely on wishful/magical thinking as a substitute for rational prediction. Sometimes they consist of nothing more than an appeal to ignorance: that we can't predict the future, and so (irrationally) we must keep doing what we are currently doing.

Behavior wise, you can't really tell the difference between ESxP and ENxP. They're super super similar. ESxP want to be taking in all of the sensory information of everything around them. They want to taste the food, they want to feel the textures, hear the sounds. They want to experience it all.

Se types jump from physical experience to physical experience. They just want to experience and enjoy all the physical aspects of the world. This is why Se types are often associated with sports and being fit. But, Se types can become indulgent and just pig out on food all day.

Ne types are similar, except they don't focus on the physical experience anywhere near as much. The physical experience becomes sort of like a medium for them to move to some new thing, that's completely unrelated to the thing they just experienced. Ne types cannot stand stagnation, or any sort of sedentary lifestyles. Everything in the external needs to be moving and changing. New possibilities must be coming in.

Se types want new sensations. Touch, taste, sound, etc.
Ne types want new objects that can reveal potential. New people, new surroundings, etc.

>strip naked your thoughts and feelings and know them deeply, and they cannot control you

Self-insight is a good thing and can help you, but emotional problems can still control you no matter how much self-awareness you have. I would argue that the majority of people who belong to the first two categories both walk with a limp; the second group just accepts their weaknesses and limitations and makes alterations to their activities and lifestyle to make things easier on themselves, whereas the first group attempts to live similarly to how they would have were they emotionally healthy. I think both groups limp, though - most people who are significantly emotionally unwell remain that way long-term, even if their unhealthiness becomes watered down.

For me, I'm a combination of 1 and 2. I stripped naked my thoughts and feelings in the early 10s and that was helpful and that self-awareness allowed me to come up with some coping mechanisms, but it's far from a cure. I still take things easy on myself in the ways that I require - namely having a calm, isolated existence.

I wouldn't really call it a self-fulfilling diagnosis, especially since in your case the idea came from your psychologist. It's more along the lines of: When you attach labels to aspects of yourself, those parts of yourself begin to "crystalize" from your own perspective. They (the aspect of yourself) become immovable, or unchangeable. There's a whole host of crazy behaviors associated with that.

This concept is also related to the judgement functions of Jung, as their goal is to "Define what things are". Which is to set a parameter, and anything that falls into those parameters is that thing. A square has four equal sides, for example. A triangle is not a square because it does not have four sides. A bad person commits murder. A good person does not commit murder.
This same exact process can be done with parts of your personality, and can lead to believing that parts of yourself cannot be changed. This is a negative to the way psychology is practiced today.

>>71631185
Close, but you're backwards. You refer to the internal way too much. Hyper self awareness, aka self conscious. I should clarify, hyper self-awareness does not result in awareness of all things within the self. It's a hyper fixation on a specific aspect of the self, internal tunnel vision is another way to think about it. It often creates visceral emotions like fear, anxiety and disgust, amongst others. The point of these emotions, aka urges, is to cause change typically, they urge you to do something about the external world through fight or flight, can also be a positive emotion though.

Your specific internal tunnel vision seems to be focused on the specific emotional state, or urge, and thus you miss the thing that sparks the urge. Since you miss the "spark" you have no foundation on which to base the rest of your interaction. It's like trying to get on a train, except the train left the station 15 minutes ago.
I would call your awareness of the external "enough to not die" or "barely enough just enough". I say "enough to not die" with intent, as well, because your reaction is that of someone facing death. It's very primal and visceral. Archaic, to use a Jungian word. In those moments you're acting purely on your inferior emotional based instinct, which is fueled by your "barely just enough" awareness of the external.

The solution to your problem is to adjust the "tool which you use to observe the internal machinations of your consciousness" and alter that tool so that the lens has a variable variable zoom to alter the resolution at which you view "yourself". Currently you're mega, mega zoomed in. You're looking at this one little aspect at a super high resolution, and that is the cause of your problem. You need to lower the resolution and zoom out to see the whole thing. Then you'll be able to see from where the "spark" originates, then next time you'll know where to be looking to see the "spark" in its entirety.
